@article{Michel1987,
abstract = {We propose a model for pulsar emission which suggests a number of tests based on existing data and additional tests given future data sets. We reexamine the idea of pulsar emission in the form of coherent curvature radiation from particle "bunches" following curved magnetic field lines near the neutron star, where the field lines are assumed not to be purely dipolar. The radiation is assumed to be concentrated on relatively narrow isolated flux tubes which generate wide individual fan beams. A given pulsar may rotate into view several such beams, leading to complex pulse profiles. The circular polarization profiles of many pulsars, wherein the sense of circular polarization reverses at maximum total intensity, are directly obtained if a single flux tube dominates the output. The " orthogonal " mode changes (often taken to represent complex emission processes) are here interpreted as arising from the overlap of two fan beams, hence possibly a geometric effect (strict orthog-onality is not guaranteed). The inferred Lorentz factors are only of the order of 100 and the accelerating potential drops are only of the order of 10 8 V, for typical pulsar parameters. Radiation is not from a "hollow cone" but rather concentrated near the low latitude edge of the magnetic polar cap, which is tipped at some angle to the spin axis. We show that this is in fact the preferred discharge region. The model suggests that the emission properties of individual flux tubes can be isolated in the data, and perhaps scaling laws predicting the spectral properties of the radiation can be deduced in the future. One observation of immediate interest is whether or not the width of subpulses is strongly correlated with the degree of circular polarization change during the pulse. A simple physical model that would lead to such phenomenology would be a magnetically guided discharge between an electrified sphere and an orbiting disk, but the phenomenology itself does not uniquely require such a model.},
