@article{Manchester1975,
abstract = {Observations of the complete polarization characteristics of individual pulses at frequencies between 110 and 450 MHz are presented for a total of 12 pulsars, together with linear polarization characteristics at 1400 MHz for four pulsars. Subpulses are often highly polarized, with linear polarization generally dominating over circular ; the variation of position angle within a subpulse is usually less than 30°. Weakly polarized subpulses are also common, with the fractional polarization generally different at different longitudes. Significant circular polarization is observed in several pulsars, in some cases apparently retaining the same sense through a subpulse, and in other cases reversing in sense within a subpulse. In many pulsars, particularly at low frequencies, the position angle of successive subpulses is quite stable for most of the profile. For certain components, however, subpulses are sometimes observed with position angle orthogonal to the most common angle. These orthogonally polarized subpulses appear to be a general feature of pulsar radio emission, and are observed in at least one component of nearly all the pulsars studied. Apart from their orthogonal position angle, they appear to have very similar properties to normal subpulses. An interpretation based on self-absorption in the emission region is discussed. The pulsars studied include several with strong, drifting subpulses. Orthogonal emission is also observed in these sources, with the leading edge of the subpulse at one angle and the trailing edge at the orthogonal angle; the position angle transition drifts across the profile with the subpulses. The orthogonal emission contributes to depolarization of integrated profiles. For most sources, the position angle of subpulses becomes more random at higher frequencies, this being the primary reason for the smaller fractional polarization observed in integrated profiles at higher frequencies.},
